This is the first time I had to apply for food stamp in 28 years after losing my job.  I was there recently and on the first day, I waited 2 hours to submitted my application.  The worker was super nice.  She gave me an appointment for the next day.

<Review>Not satisfied with the overall experience with this company.

My wife and I purchased a rental of 2 bikes (1 regular and 1 with a baby seat). They treated the rental as 3 bikes when I returned it at a drop off location and I was charged 3 times for the drop off fee which was not disclosed during our discussion with the representative in store. In addition to the drop off location situation, I had a company representative reach out to me 3 times to ask me the same questions each time (where was it dropped off, what time, and where did you drop of the keys). Each time I told them the same information. What was not disclosed was that you must tell the bike rental store representative that you are dropping it off at a drop off location. Had I known we were supposed to call ahead about dropping off the bikes I would have done it as instructed.

In common with the rest of reviews on here, the bikes were not exactly kept up with the wear and tear. I would not be surprised if we had not purchased the insurance that they would ding us for the minor scratches and other wear and tear parts on the bike.

I will not be using this company again if we are ever back at San Fransisco and warn others to us a different company or to simply read this review as a full disclosure of what to do when you rent "3" bikes.<//Review>< Pics>

<Time>1467682648730</Time><Rating>1<//Rating>< Text>
I rarely write reviews for places but feel I need to in this case due to my poor experience with Bay City.  My wife and I rented bikes there to sight-see in San Francisco this past week.  About an hour into our ride, my wife's bike broke while changing gears going up a small hill.  Bay City was good about coming out to replace the bike but when we returned later that day, we were told we were being assessed a $45 fee for breaking the bike.  I wouldn‚Äôt have minded paying the fee if we had not used proper care with the bike or if something got stolen but to be charged for something that was clearly due to the bike not being in good condition and was no fault of our own was completely ridiculous.  The bike was making noises when she was changing gears throughout the first hour of our ride and it was clear this was not a good bike and was the primary reason for the bike breaking.

When I called Bay City to talk about this further the next day I was told we caused the bike to break due to ‚Äúuser error‚Äù from changing gears while going up a hill.  The manager indicated we should have been told this when we rented (we weren‚Äôt, we were told to make sure we‚Äôre pedaling while changing gears, which she was doing).  Even if we had been told this, I would expect a good bike to at the very most just have the chain come off, not for the entire gear system to break.  Also, if you‚Äôre renting bikes in a city like San Francisco, it might be good to have bikes that can withstand changing gears on small hills since there are hills everywhere.

If you are planning on renting bikes in San Francisco, I would strongly recommend not using Bay City.  Any place that will charge you for such a ridiculous thing does not deserve your business.< /Text>

< text>
We found a deal for this place on Groupon - 4 bikes for 24 hours only $60 (after a special 20% off). It's a very doable walk to here from the cruise port if you're coming from there like we did. We were so grateful for the Yelp check-in offer of a free water bottle. I used mine when we got the bike and hubby used his when we returned them. We spent an extra $20 for a kids trailer for our seven month old. You can also get a child's seat for the same price. We were all given helmets, which were included in the Groupon price. Just a heads up though - our seventh month old's head was forced forward in an awkward way when wearing the helmet and riding in the trailer. However, the trailer itself was great! We'd never used a trailer before so we looked this one up on line. It's definitely one of the more expensive trailers and had fantastic reviews. If it were to flip, it's steel frame would protect the child.

Service was friendly! My one and only complaint is that they didn't offer a bike with a banana seat - my but was sore at the end of the day!< /text>

< text>
My friend and I had a horrible experience when doing the ride across the Golden Gate Bridge. We booked the ride through a lady in a tourist centre, who didn't even seem sure of what she was doing anyway!! When we turned up for the bike ride they said we can only go if we book the Alcatraz with it as it comes as a package. Well we did want to do the Alcatraz anyway so the man managed to juggle things about and we paid for that trip too. God knows how it all got so cocked up in the first place
Anyway, he told us we had been upgraded to 'hybrid bikes' even though we hadn't requested them...and had never even ridden one before!,
My friend had not been on a bike for many years so when we tried these things out they were far too powerful for us. I kept mine and switched it to manual but she requested an ordinary bike which they gave her, but would not refund the $20 each that they had charged us for having these hybrid bikes!! He did make a concession though and hands us a bottle of water each!
The blurb on the information leaflet says this tour is suitable for families and BEGINNERS
I am here to tell you that this bike ride is NOT for beginners. In fact I thought it was downright dangerous at times. And neither of us (55 year olds) realised when we booked it that it was to end in Sausalito
They young guys who lead (one at the front and one at the back) were ok..especially the one who had to stay at the back with my friend and I ....but I think he was getting a bit worried about us. The front leader guy lied several times that each hill was worse than the next...they were all bad! And when I naively asked how we would get up to the bridge, he said there's an elevator. Yes I know I shouldn't have fallen for that, but it was all so totally unexpected. We had to walk our bikes uphill  quite a few times, but then the downhill slopes and bends were even scarier because some of the roads had no sides!!,
I kept turning round to see if my poor friend was ok, or if she was even still,THERE, and not crushed on the road somewhere.
The bridge itself is very frightening I found, because the seasoned cyclists are all so fast and aggressive, you daren't wobble into their pathway!!
Ok we are glad we achieved it, and got out of it alive, but I do not have any good memories of it. Only getting off the ferry at the end and dumping that bike back on Bay City Bikes! (Thanks to Julius for his patience!)</text>

<Review>(Translated by Google) Just great,
and one of the best recommendations for San Francisco.

The tour is very well organized. Our tour guide drove up and at the end of the group, someone was careful that no one is lost. It is stopped at regular intervals to get to know. Just before the bridge there's an extra stop (toilet, coffee, ice, ...) to take really good pictures.

The moment when you drive over the bridge - indescribable !! Unfortunately, it is difficult to take pictures because there are logically many people on the way. It is possible. At the end you get the opportunity to stay in Sausalito. Or you can take the ferry back (ticket not included, $ 12 / person, bike is free).
All in all, highly recommended and I would do it again :-) and
So a 100% recommendation from me.

It is hard to find a company whom you can trust to give excellent service and will not cheat you. We have been fortunate enough to find Diamond Auto Body. My husband and I have gone to Diamond Auto Body for three separate occasions - once for a new windshield, and twice for auto body work. They have gone above and beyond, coordinating with the car rental company and the insurance company. Besides the excellent customer service we received there, the work on our vehicles was impeccable. We will not trust our vehicles to any other auto body company.

I must add - the three cars they have worked on are a 2001 Ford F150, a 2005 Scion XB, and a 2014 Toyota Rav 4 - all of which do not even total $75,000. I was still treated with the same respect as the people with the fancy cars.

I want to end with an observation that speaks to their customer service - the other day I saw an accident not too far away from the business. I saw one of the employees helping a gentleman push his car to the side of the street away from main traffic. I don't know too many companies who would do that, especially in the heat.<//review>

In response to a review made by "Google User," 2 years ago below, the exam maneuver done to the uncircumcised penis is both common, typical, and appropriate for his age.  You don't force it open, but you do have to test it's re-tractability as well as the placement of the urethra to ensure the patient doesn't have hypospadias, which might be missed if still in diapers.  We pediatricians are still taught to do it to this day, for a variety of reasons, (also worth mentioning is to make sure that the foreskin isn't too taught and cutting off circulation.)  She did exactly what she should do, and myself and many of my colleagues do the same.

<review>Dr. D'Sylva has been my kids' pediatrician since the day after my daughter was born.  Due to some complications, my daughter had to be moved to a local hospital with NICU.  You don't know the horror of having someone come in to tell you that your newborn baby has to be taken from you.  At that moment, Dr. D'Sylva was the doctor on call at the hospital and had been quietly monitoring our daughter until the moment she decided that my daughter's lungs were not clearing up as they should and needed to be moved to the NICU.  When she walked into our room, a close friend was visiting and recognized her immediately as she was her kids' pediatrician as well.  Knowing our friend approved, who doesn't easily give glowing reviews, approved of Dr. D'Sylva made us more at ease.  Even as she told us what was going on with our daughter, despite that initial feeling any parent would have, she was immediately putting us at ease.  My daughter spent a week in the NICU and Dr. D'Sylva constantly checked in on her despite the fact that we weren't officially her patient yet and were at another hospital.

Since then Dr. D'Sylva has been our pediatrician and we have been more than pleased.  Yes some times we have to wait longer than we want at her office, but what doctor's office is perfect.  She has a great way with kids and is able to calm them even when giving shots.  My kids simply adore her.  Never have I seen kids so happy to go to the doctor's office as mine but the moment we say Dr. D'Sylva they are excited.  She also returns our calls, even some of the dumb first time parent ones, promptly.

One last thing that I appreciate with Dr. D'Sylva is she gives us options.  To often doctors seem to try force you in one direction or another, but she has always given us pros and cons of any option faced before us.

If you searching for a pediatrician for your children, then I would highly recommend Dr. Yvonne D'Sylva.< /review><Time>1611063863710< /Time>< user_name>

Yvonne D'Sylva is an amazing woman! She dedicates her entire life to children. She was my pediatrician when I was a baby and now she is my daughters. The wait might be long and the building is old, but it is NOT dirty and she is well worth the wait! There are toys in the waiting room for children, so I don't know why a previous review said there wasn't? Maybe they don't have toys in the separate sick child waiting room... Im pretty sure we can all figure out why there wouldn't be toys in a room for contagious children to play with. She sings to your child and looks them in the eye, gets on their level. Anytime my daughter has shots she will cry while getting them, but as soon as Dr. is done she stops crying (probably because she is singing to her). My son, Taylor, has been living in the Shoreline Sober Living house on Gardena Road for the last 6 months while he has been a client at Shoreline Recovery Center.  He graduated this week from Shoreline and  has moved to another sober living house in Del Mar.  Enough good cannot be said about the house managers, Mike and Shane. They set some pretty high expectation for  their clients, but not beyond their reach.  They take a personal interest in making sure that your son is getting what is required for his success. Shoreline sober living provided me the guidance, support and structure I needed in early recovery.  After completing treatment, my counselors strongly advised that I attend Shoreline sober living.  Now, after several years of sobriety, I am grateful that I followed that recommendation. My time at Shoreline was the single greatest contributing factor in my path to becoming a highly productive, sober member of society.  I now work in recovery as counselor, which has given me an insider‚Äôs perspective on how Shoreline compares to other sober living programs, and as a result, my appreciation for this program has only grown. The structure of Shoreline‚Äôs program is not like any other you will find in the area. What separates Shoreline from other homes is the culture of comradery, and even more importantly, the level of accountability. Upon entering Shoreline I was accepted with open arms and the residents integrated me into the community quickly- showing me the ins and outs of the daily routines, the best meetings to attend and setting me up with a solid sponsor.  I was also introduced by my fellow residents to many people in the recovery community outside of Shoreline that I now consider friends. I saw this process repeated with each new resident.  Looking back now, I realize how imperative this experience was to my recovery.  Finding and becoming part of a sober community is of paramount importance and Shoreline facilitates this experience in a way that other recovery homes don‚Äôt. Aaron, the Program Manager, does a great job of fostering a positive atmosphere while stressing the importance of a balanced life that includes work, fellowship, commitment, goal setting, financial responsibility and community.  The entire staff, from the top down, genuinely care about helping each resident find success in sobriety and they work closely with each resident to assist in the transition from treatment back into the stream of life. Shoreline‚Äôs location couldn‚Äôt be better since Encinitas is home to an active, robust recovery community.  The houses are centrally located and close to the beach. There is plenty of opportunity for employment in the surrounding area and the houses are walking distance to the gym and shopping centers.  The houses themselves are immaculate and kept clean. I am eternally grateful for the experience I received at Shoreline, and highly recommend this program to anyone looking to find lasting recovery.<//Text>

Following a lengthy, 120 day stay at a local San Diego County inpatient treatment facility, he stayed at Shoreline for over a year and since then has maintained contact with the community.  Throughout his stay we were most appreciative of Shoreline's continual weekly progress calls, advice, expertise on addiction and desire to help not only our son, but also all of our family navigate the difficulties that arise throughout the different stages of getting free of intoxicating substances. During his three prior unsuccessful attempts to become free of drug use at nationally known inpatient treatment centers, we never fully understood, nor was there much attempt made by those facilities to make us aware of the critical role a sober living facility and ongoing outpatient treatment provides in achieving lasting recovery. Thirty days of inpatient treatment followed by nothing more than AA meetings and good intentions was a recipe for relapse. During his last in-patient recovery at a well known facility here in San Diego County, they stressed both the need for at least 90 days of in-patient treatment and for an extended period of transition with outpatient treatment while living in a structured sober living facility where continued sobriety is bolstered through ongoing testing, experienced staff and and a community of peers who are also seeking lasting recovery.  Shoreline Sober Living is such a facility. We are extremely grateful for all they have done for our son and us.<//Review><pics>None</pics>< Resp>
None< /Resp>

<Text>As a former client of Shoreline Sober Living, I was very pleased with going through the program and interacting with the staff. During my active addiction, life was falling apart at every seam and filled with negativity, doubt, hatred. The awesome part of the Shoreline program was that once I got sober, I learned how to live sober. I was taught how to take care of things like chores, keeping my possessions organized, being accountable to not only myself, but people around, and building trustworthy relationships. I learned how to take care of the little things so that when it was time for the big things, I wouldn't get overwhelmed and be prepared to handle whatever life throws my way.  Almost reaching a year clean and it's all thanks to this program. I would definitely recommend it anyone who is willing to do what it takes to get a better life and one that is full of happiness, positive energy, and purpose.< /Text>< Name>

<GmapID>0x80869e47f2b4da07:0xa8052acc82c297b6</GmapID>< text>
Beautiful location! Can't beat the views! The trail down to the beach is unpaved with many steps (not handicapped accessable), no railings, be careful with small children and elderly. Great place to hang out for the day, bring a lunch and maybe beach umbrella as there is no shade. Bathrooms are in the parking lot area and so are garbages. Clean up after yourselves to keep the beach trash free! Go during low tide to check out the tide pools, we saw a variety of sea life including two giant star fish!<//text>

< review>
Beautiful area. Easy access to the beach and trails north and south. During lowish tide you can walk to multiple beaches and be totally alone. Tide pools galore and lovely views from the trails.<//review>

<text>This shopping center has changed a great deal over the years.  (Some for better, some for worse depending on who you are talking to.)  Overall has some good stores and the smaller stores within the center are usually not crowded.  Has been slowly taken over by larger "Box" stores in recent years.  (This is usually the reason for the "it's better, it's worse discussion).
I am one who is definitely nostalgic for the old days of the man made pond and stream with it's bridges and walk ways; but it needed the revitalization as the economy crashed and business vacated the buildings.  So I think the changes were good for the area even if the appeal of the area and unique walk ways and paths had to go.  (Old pond/stream and pedestrian only path was filled in and became a parking lot.)</text>< user>

<pictures>None</pictures><user_id>104185530817267798803< /user_id><username>miss jill< /username><Date>1558237829737</Date>< Text>
Market Place in the early nineties was a thriving glorified strip mall across from Sunrise Mall. The mall has since lost its appeal being mostly a place you take your 15 year old to practice for their driving test. Market Place and the general area is transient now. I personally stop into the Walmart only in an emergency, the store is always freezing, and the employees are just awful. Customer service closes at 8:00 pm that means 7:00 to them. There is really nothing else I would go there for. It is as well abandoned so parking is never an issue. Best Buy, Michaels, Steinmart, Old Navy, Barns and Noble, Starbucks (isn't everyone sick of Starbucks), AAA, Jamba Juice, Famous Footwear, Cost Plus some scattered eatting establishments, banks, a red box and other stores. The way its laid out it really doesn't make any sense. A big parking lot with stores dropped in here and there. Boring<//Text>

< date>
1558237829737< /date>
<Rate>3<//Rate>< text>
Market Place in the early nineties was a thriving glorified strip mall across from Sunrise Mall. The mall has since lost its appeal being mostly a place you take your 15 year old to practice for their driving test. Market Place and the general area is transient now. I personally stop into the Walmart only in an emergency, the store is always freezing, and the employees are just awful. Customer service closes at 8:00 pm that means 7:00 to them. There is really nothing else I would go there for. It is as well abandoned so parking is never an issue. Best Buy, Michaels, Steinmart, Old Navy, Barns and Noble, Starbucks (isn't everyone sick of Starbucks), AAA, Jamba Juice, Famous Footwear, Cost Plus some scattered eatting establishments, banks, a red box and other stores. The way its laid out it really doesn't make any sense. A big parking lot with stores dropped in here and there. Boring<//text>
